---
description: TripPalette naming — TP prefix for Views, ViewModels, and Models
alwaysApply: true
---

# Naming: TP prefix

- All SwiftUI `View` types (and `UIViewRepresentable`) must start with `TP` and end with `View` (e.g. `TPCalendarView`, `TPDayCellView`).
- All view models must start with `TP` and end with `ViewModel` (e.g. `TPCalendarViewModel`).
- All models must start with `TP` (e.g. `TPPeriod`, `TPPeriodDraft`).
- Screen folders are named `TP(Name)Screen`.
- Do not introduce bare names like `CalendarView`, `CalendarViewModel`, or `TripPeriod`.

```swift
// ❌ BAD
struct CalendarView: View { ... }
final class CalendarViewModel: ObservableObject { ... }
struct TripPeriod: Identifiable { ... }

// ✅ GOOD
struct TPCalendarView: View { ... }
final class TPCalendarViewModel: ObservableObject { ... }
struct TPPeriod: Identifiable { ... }
```

# ViewModel state: use ViewState, not many `@Published` fields

- Do not scatter UI state across multiple `@Published` properties on the view model.
- Put screen UI state into a single `TP(Name)ViewState` struct.
- The view model exposes one `@Published` (or `@Published private(set)`) `state: TP(Name)ViewState`.
- Mutate state by copying → changing → reassigning (so SwiftUI always gets a publish).
- Views read data via `viewModel.state.*` and call view model methods for actions.

```swift
// ❌ BAD
final class TPCalendarViewModel: ObservableObject {
    @Published var periods: [TPPeriod] = []
    @Published var selectedDates: Set<DateComponents> = []
    @Published var displayMode: TPCalendarDisplayMode = .month
    @Published var focusedMonth: DateComponents
}

// ✅ GOOD
struct TPCalendarViewState: Equatable {
    var periods: [TPPeriod] = []
    var selectedDates: Set<DateComponents> = []
    var displayMode: TPCalendarDisplayMode = .month
    var focusedMonth: DateComponents
}

final class TPCalendarViewModel: ObservableObject {
    @Published private(set) var state: TPCalendarViewState
}
```

# Screen assembly: use Factory

- Each screen has `TP(Name)Factory` as a `@MainActor final class` with a static method `configure()` that returns a ready-to-show view.
- Wire dependencies inside `configure()` and return the view. Call sites only do `TP(Name)Factory.configure()`.
- Do not add private wrapper views or separate `makeRouter` / `makeViewModel` / `makeView` helpers unless needed.

```swift
// ❌ BAD
enum TPCalendarFactory { ... }
struct TPCalendarFactory { ... }
TPCalendarView(viewModel: TPCalendarViewModel(router: TPCalendarRouter()))

// ✅ GOOD
@MainActor
final class TPCalendarFactory {
    static func configure() -> some View {
        let router = TPCalendarRouter()
        let viewModel = TPCalendarViewModel(router: router)
        let view = TPCalendarView(viewModel: viewModel)
        return view
    }
}

TPCalendarFactory.configure()
```

# Screen folder structure

Each `TP(Name)Screen` folder contains:

- The main screen view: `TP(Name)View.swift`
- The view model: `TP(Name)ViewModel.swift`
- The view state: `TP(Name)ViewState.swift`
- The factory: `TP(Name)Factory.swift`
- The router if needed: `TP(Name)Router.swift`
- Optional screen-level helpers (e.g. date utilities)

Smaller/supporting views go into a nested `View/` folder:

```
TPCalendarScreen/
  TPCalendarFactory.swift
  TPCalendarView.swift
  TPCalendarViewModel.swift
  TPCalendarViewState.swift
  TPCalendarRouter.swift
  TPCalendarDate.swift
  View/
    TPDayCellView.swift
    TPMonthSectionView.swift
    TPYearGridView.swift
```
